{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637901"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:47:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:47:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17680"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17680"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.18,0.25,0.07,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71923"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10394"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57393"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8483"},{"type":"tags","id":"10486"},{"type":"tags","id":"10488"},{"type":"tags","id":"10489"},{"type":"tags","id":"10490"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24295"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71923"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe glomerular filtration rate depends on several opposing pressures across the glomerular capillary membrane. One of these pressures acts within Bowman\u0027s capsule.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes capsular hydrostatic pressure in the normal human kidney?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["45 mmHg opposing filtration","15 mmHg opposing filtration","60 mmHg favouring filtration","0 mmHg with no effect on filtration","30 mmHg favouring filtration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecapsular hydrostatic pressure is approximately 15 mmHg and opposes filtration\u003C/strong\u003E. This pressure exists within Bowman\u0027s capsule and works against the glomerular filtration pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E45 mmHg opposing filtration\u003C/strong\u003E - This pressure would be too high and would severely reduce glomerular filtration rate.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E60 mmHg favouring filtration\u003C/strong\u003E - Capsular hydrostatic pressure always opposes filtration and cannot favour it. This value is also much too high.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0 mmHg with no effect on filtration\u003C/strong\u003E - Some pressure must always exist within Bowman\u0027s capsule due to the presence of filtered fluid.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E30 mmHg favouring filtration\u003C/strong\u003E - Capsular hydrostatic pressure always opposes filtration and cannot favour it.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe net filtration pressure is determined by the balance between the glomerular capillary hydrostatic pressure (approximately 55 mmHg favouring filtration), plasma oncotic pressure (approximately 30 mmHg opposing filtration), and capsular hydrostatic pressure (approximately 15 mmHg opposing filtration).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Capsular hydrostatic pressure opposes glomerular filtration pressure in the kidney.","Normal capsular hydrostatic pressure is approximately 15 mmHg in humans.","Increased capsular hydrostatic pressure reduces the net filtration pressure and glomerular filtration rate."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57393"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17680"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57393"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T20:10:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T20:11:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10394"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71923"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"http